\begin_layout Standard
What can I do,
 and what do I want to do,
 with this 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 vector?
 I can use it to calculate the force a ball feels when placed on the ramp,
 or the vector (in 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{3}$
\end_inset

) orthogonal to the ramp,
 but both of these are specific cases of something more general:
 we want to recover the shape of the ramp from the 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be more specific,
 we want to solve the following problem:
 Given the 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 vector,
 which encodes the direction and slope of the ramp,
 we want to recover the function 
\begin_inset Formula $h(x,y)$
\end_inset

,
 which given a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 returns the height of the ramp at that point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note:
 Since the 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 vector only gives us information about the slope,
 we cannot expect to fully determine 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 we will establish that at 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 the ramp is at a known height 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore,
 in order not to worry about the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

,
 let us assume that the ramp has been extended to cover the whole space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution to our problem is not particularly difficult.
 The graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a plane,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 must be of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(x,y)=ax+by+c.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $h(A)$
\end_inset

 is known to be 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 we can write this in a more convenient manner
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(p)=(a,b)\cdot(p-A)+h_{0}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

,
 recall first that the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to level sets.
 Looking at the figure above,
 we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is also orthogonal to level sets (this is in fact what we meant when we said 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 points in the downhill direction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

),
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)=\alpha s$
\end_inset

 for some real number 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To discover 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

,
 we can use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $h(B)$
\end_inset

 is known,
 plugging 
\begin_inset Formula $h(B)=h_{0}-13$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha s\cdot(B-A)=-13.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $s=B-A$
\end_inset

 in our coordinate system and 
\begin_inset Formula $\norm{B-A}=\sqrt{13}$
\end_inset

,
 we conclude 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=-1$
\end_inset

,
 hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(p)=h_{0}-s\cdot(p-A).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Slightly more generally,
 it is a trivial exercise to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p)-h(q)=-s\cdot(p-q)$
\end_inset

,
 so in some sense,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 vector serves as a ruler which which one can measure height differences.
 This is,
 in fact,
 an apt way to think about 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

,
 and the way we are thinking about 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

,
 is very closely related to the euclidean inner product.
 The inner product has an important property:
 while it behaves well under isometries,
 it gets distorted under other changes of coordinates.
 For example,
 if we rescale the whole map by a factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 along with it,
 the above formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p)$
\end_inset

 ceases to work.
 For example,
 
\begin_inset Formula $h(B)$
\end_inset

 (recall that in rigour I should be writing 
\begin_inset Formula $B'$
\end_inset

) is meant to be equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{0}-13$
\end_inset

,
 but if 
\begin_inset Formula $s'$
\end_inset

 is the rescaled vector we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{0}-(B-A)\cdot s'=h_{0}-(1.5,1)\cdot(1.5,1)=h_{0}-\frac{13}{4}\neq h_{0}-13.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

