\begin_layout Standard
This notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scaling differently
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is at the heart of the idea of a covector.
 It is kind of like a vector,
 but it behaves very differently under changes of coordinates.
 And this change is made in order to retain a very specific aspect:
 if the vectors of the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are scaled in some manner,
 the covectors are scaled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inversely
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in order to preserve inner products between vectors and covectors!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this manner,
 the role of covectors is to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

be inner product'd with vectors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In some sense,
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

most natural setting
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the scalar product of two vectors is actually between a vector and a covector,
 because it becomes independent of our coordinate system.
 The way we scale covectors relative to vectors will ensure that the scalar product is independent of the chosen basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But then,
 the notion of scalar product becomes somewhat superfluous.
 If all we're going to do with covectors is to use them to obtain numbers from vectors (and add covectors to each other and stuff),
 we might as well define a covector as a thing that turns vectors into numbers.
 But this is precisely the notion of dual vector:
 that is,
 an element of the dual space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall the definition of dual space:
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the set of linear functions from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

 (or whatever field the vector space is over).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion:
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a vector space,
 we use the name vector for elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

,
 and covectors for elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{*}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
How it fits together
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now recall elementary linear algebra to figure out how to make sense of the relation between this notion of covector and the scaling properties mentioned before.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First of all,
 how to represent a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 in coordinates?
 Since a covector is a different kind of object from a vector,
 fixing a basis of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 does not allow us to represent 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 in as a linear combination of the 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two distinct but equivalent ways to handle the subject matter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Dual Basis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\braket}[1]{}
{\langle#1\rangle}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the simplest way.
 Given a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

,
 we define the so-called dual basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{1},\dots,\omega^{n}$
\end_inset

 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega^{i}(e_{j})=\delta_{ij},\text{ or equivalently }\omega^{i}(\sum_{j}x_{j}e_{j})=x_{i}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then,
 any covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 can be written as a linear combination of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{i}$
\end_inset

,
 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda(x)=\lambda\left(\sum x_{i}e_{i}\right)=\lambda\left(\sum\omega^{i}(x)e_{i}\right)=\sum\lambda(e_{i})\omega^{i}(x),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
whence 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\sum\lambda(e_{i})\omega^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 we can consider the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 in some basis as 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 applied to the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th vector of this basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bonus:
 Compare the following three formulas to write a vector or a covector in coordinates.
 The first is the usual formula for the coordinates of a vector in orthonormal coordinates (assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 has an inner product),
 while the other two write a vector in the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 or a covector in the dual basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega^{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
v=\sum\braket{v,e_{i}}e_{i},\\
v=\sum\omega^{i}(v)e_{i},\\
\lambda=\sum\lambda(e_{i})\omega^{i}.
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Matrix Form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This form is slightly more enlightening,
 because as well as telling us what the coordinates are,
 it also tells us how they should be organized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall from linear algebra that when we record the coordinates of a vector in some basis we do so in column-matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall also that given a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T\colon V\to W$
\end_inset

,
 a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

,
 we record the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coordinates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 in a matrix.
 This matrix is of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim W\times\dim V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As it turns out,
 the convention of writing vectors as column-matrices can be seen as a particular case of this process:
 to specify an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is the same as to specify a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $\R\to W$
\end_inset

,
 yielding a matrix of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\dim W\times1$
\end_inset

.
 It stands to reason that a dual vector,
 which is a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $V\to\R$
\end_inset

,
 should be represented as a vector of size 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times\dim V$
\end_inset

;
 in other words,
 a row-vector!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What should the coordinates be?
 In this,
 we find the same answer as before (which is why the two points of view are equivalent).
 Recall from linear algebra that in order to represent 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 as a matrix,
 one must first specify a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{v_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{w_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

,
 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $ij$
\end_inset

-th element of said matrix is the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th coordinate (in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $Tv_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 In our case,
 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

,
 and the most natural basis is the single vector 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

,
 and so we conclude that (given a basis 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

) it is natural to represent a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 in coordinates as the row-matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}\lambda(e_{1}) & \dots & \lambda(e_{n})\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This representation has two benefits.
 One,
 it reminds us that vectors and covectors are fundamentally different objects,
 which could be lost on us if we represented both as mere sequences of numbers.
 Two,
 it leads to a nice identity for application of covectors in local coordinates.
 Given a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

,
 some basis,
 a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 be their coordinate representations.
 Then,
 the following identity holds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda(v)=\hat{\lambda}\hat{v}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Coordinate Changes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset FormulaMacro
\newcommand{\tr}{\intercal}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To conclude this section and move on to more visual stuff,
 let us discuss how covectors (or rather,
 their representations) change under changes of basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{1},\dots,e_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 be two different bases of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in V^{*}$
\end_inset

,
 denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{e}$
\end_inset

 the coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 basis,
 and likewise for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be the matrix whose 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-th column is the coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 basis.
 Then,
 linear algebra relates the representation of a vector in both bases by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{e}=Bv_{f}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How does it relate the representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{e}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f}$
\end_inset

?
 From the identities we have already deduced,
 we conclude
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{f}=\begin{bmatrix}\lambda(f_{1}) & \dots & \lambda(f_{n})\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\lambda_{e}(f_{1})_{e} & \dots & \lambda_{e}(f_{n})_{e}\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and from a little bit of matrix block multiplication we reach the conclusion
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{f}=\lambda_{e}\begin{bmatrix}(f_{1})_{e} & \dots & (f_{n})_{e}\end{bmatrix}=\lambda_{e}B.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compare the two formulas:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{e}=Bv_{f},\quad\lambda_{e}=\lambda_{f}B^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formulas are identical,
 except that 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 has been sent to the other side and inverted.
 This is as it should be,
 as it ensures that the formula 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(v)=\lambda_{e}v_{e}$
\end_inset

 holds in any basis,
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{e}v_{e}=\lambda_{f}B^{-1}Bv_{f}=\lambda_{f}v_{f}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This last argument can be used as a mnemonic in a pinch to deduce how coordinates of covectors ought to change in order to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

preserve the dot product
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that we are representing the coordinates of the covector as a row-matrix.
 Note how,
 if we represented them in a column-matrix,
 the formulas would become slightly more awkward.
 The coordinates represented in a column-matrix are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{e})^{\tr}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{f})^{\tr}$
\end_inset

,
 and so we conclude
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\lambda_{e})^{\tr}=(B^{-1})^{\tr}(\lambda_{f})^{\tr},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
in other words,
 if the vector coordinates have changed by 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 then the covector coordinates have changed by 
\begin_inset Formula $(B^{-1})^{\tr}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

