 when measuring slopes in a coordinate-independent way,
 the notion of covector is more robust with regard to coordinate changes than a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

regular
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 vector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A covector can be defined as a linear transformation from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

.
 This makes sense intuitively (because to measure a slope is to assign a height to each number) and formally (because the coordinates scale as we want them to).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can visualize such covectors,
 not as arrows,
 but as stacked (oriented) hyperplanes,
 an infinity of them an infinitesimal distance from each other.
 Under this picture,
 evaluation of a covector on a vector amounts to counting how many hyperplanes the vector crosses.
\end_layout

