\begin_layout Standard
Intuitively,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional manifold and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 a manifold which splits 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

an inside
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

an outside
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

inside
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 must be small in the sense that a line cannot 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

go on infinitely inside
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 For example,
 the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 would not split 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{3}$
\end_inset

 into an inside and an outside,
 because neither half-space is small in this sense:
 you have infinite line segments living in each.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An example of a set we wish to consider is 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=S^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 which splits 
\begin_inset Formula $\R^{3}$
\end_inset

 into an inside and an outside.
 The inside is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because the only way to have an infinite line inside 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is to have it wind up infinitely.
 Now,
 it is hard to express properly why such infinite winding up is disallowed,
 but if we assume that it is,
 then the inside of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 counts as small.
 We are interested in sets whose inside satisfies this property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course,
 all this intuitive handwaving is intended to convey a concept which mathematicians have figured out long ago:
 We want 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 to be the border of a manifold with boundary,
 say 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 To say that 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the inside
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) is small is to say that 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is compact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 we intend to integrate some 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Ordinarily,
 there would be no reason to believe that there would be a way to simplify this computation,
 but the hypothesis that 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 splits the space in two implies a very important fact:
 
\emph on
any line which enters 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 must either exit it again or stop inside 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore,
 if we see integrating an 
\begin_inset Formula $(n-1)$
\end_inset

-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 as counting the lines entering 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

,
