\begin_layout Subsection
Cartan's Magical Formulas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now ready to look at Cartan's magic formula for the Lie derivative,
 as we have already seen the three necessary ingredients:
 the Lie derivative,
 contraction,
 and the exterior derivative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us begin by noting the relation between these three concepts.
 Given a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and a form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

,
 both the Lie derivative and the contraction are related to the notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gluing the tip of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 into the atoms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a top form (i.e.
 its atoms are points) a useful identity appears:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Lie_{X}\omega=\dl(X\into\omega).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

