\begin_layout Standard
This identity is the first version of Cartan's magic formula,
 and it actually works whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a closed form.
 However,
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has atoms with nonempty border,
 a new term appears.
 To visualize why,
 suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is not a closed form,
 and has an atom 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with border 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial A$
\end_inset

.
 Assume for the sake of terminology that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is one-dimensional,
 so that we may call it a curve with one or two extrema.
 Then,
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\into A$
\end_inset

 is a strip.
 One of its sides is exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Let us call the opposite side 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 and the one or two other sides will be called 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 on the one hand,
 the atom corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lie_{X}\omega$
\end_inset

 is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $A+B$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\dl(X\into\omega)$
\end_inset

 includes 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 but also 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

,
 so we need to remove that term.
 A little bit of thought shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is an atom from 
\begin_inset Formula $X\into\dl\omega$
\end_inset

,
 and so,
 modulo signs,
 we reach the famous formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Lie_{X}\omega=\dl(X\into\omega)+X\into\dl\omega.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

